<DOC><DOCNO> AP891109-0318 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2338EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-ControlData-Ticketron     11-09 0220</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Control Data-Ticketron,0229</SECOND><HEAD>Control Data To Sell Ticketron to Carlyle Group</HEAD><DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Control Data Corp. said Thursday itagreed to sell its Ticketron Sports andamp; Entertainment division to theCarlyle Group, a private merchant banking firm based in Washington,D.C.   Terms were not disclosed.   Control Data said it will retain its Automated Wagering Servicesoperation, which supplies on-line wagering systems to statelotteries and off-track betting jurisdictions. The operation wasformerly part of Ticketron.   Ticketron is the nation's oldest computerized ticketing servicecompany. Last year, Ticketron sold over 19 million ticketsgenerating about $450 million in gross ticket receipts and $41.4million in revenue, while breaking even for Control Data.   ``Carlyle's strengths will build on Ticketron's solid marketpresence and reputation for customer service and make it an evenstronger competitor,'' said Lawrence Perlman, president and chiefoperating officer of Control Data. ``The sale allows Control Datato focus more resources on the growth of its Automated WageringServices operation and other businesses.''   Carlyle is owned by the Richard King Mellon family and by theCarlyle managing directors, which include Frank Carlucci, formerU.S. defense secretary.   Earlier this year, Carlyle led an investor partnership thatbought Coldwell Banker Commercial Group from Sears, Roebuck andamp; Co.   The Ticketron sale is expected to be completed in 30 days.</TEXT></DOC>